column177: neo-institutionalist approach to the different factors impacting state adoption of—or refusal to adopt—same-sex marriage laws. The now twenty-one countries where lesbians and gay men can legally marry include recent or longstanding democracies
column179: and unitary and federal states. They all reflect different positions with respect to religion and the cultural foundations of the nation. Countries opposed to such legalization
column180: and those having taken measures in recent years to legally reinforce the heterosexual fundaments of marriage
column181: present a similar diversity. This diversity
column182: in a globalized context where the idea of same-sex marriage has become integral to claims for LGBTI equality and indeed LGBTI human rights
column183: gives rise to the following question: which factors contribute to institutionalizing same-sex marriage?\n\nThe analytical framework used for exploring these factors in this book is neo-institutionalism. Through three neo-institutionalist lenses—historical
column184: sociological and discursive—contributors investigate two aspects of the processes of adoption or opposition of equal recognition of same-sex partnerships. Firstly
column185: they reveal how claims by LGBTIQ movements are being framed politically and brought to parliamentary politics. Secondly
column186: they explore the ways in which same-sex marriage becomes institutionalized (or resisted) through legal and societal norms and practices. Although it adopts neo-institutionalism as its main theoretical framework

column12: 'name': 'The Role of Rookie Female Directors in a Post‐Quota Period: Gender Inequalities within French Boards'
column13: 'publisher': 'Industrial Relations : A Journal of Economy and Society'
column14: 'description': 'The board‐level gender quota enacted in France has induced the massive arrival in corporate boards of a new population—namely
column15: women with no prior board experience. We examine the positions and the compensation of these “rookie female directors.” We show that
column16: conditional on their individual characteristics and firm effects
column17: rookie female directors have had a limited access to the key positions within boards and have suffered from a significant compensation gap. We interpret this evidence of positional segregation as resulting from gender stereotypes that have persisted in the process of rookie female directors’ integration within boards.'
column58: 'publisher': 'Handbook of the International Political Economy of the Corporation
column60: 'description': 'This chapter provides an overview of the literature on corporate governance and corporate accountability
column61: focusing on listed companies. It first surveys the normative debate on corporate responsibility
column62: opposing two antagonistic models: the shareholder primacy model and the corporate social responsibility model. It then relates this (normative) diversity to the empirical diversity in corporate governance systems. The following sections narrow the scope of the analysis
column63: to discuss in more details two crucial governance mechanisms and their effects on various firm outcomes: the distribution of stock ownership
column64: and the composition and functioning of the board of directors.'
column104: 'name': 'How to foster responsible corporate governance? Voluntary versus legislative approaches'
column110: is regulated in most jurisdictions by voluntary and legislative instruments
column111: as a way to foster good practices
column112: responsible behavior and firm performance. Understanding the relative costs and benefits of the two approaches is therefore an important question. This chapter proposes a first step in this direction
column113: by investigating and comparing how French listed companies (SBF 120) comply with the AFEP-MEDEF code of corporate governance regarding independence on one side and the mandatory board gender quota on the other. The chapter reviews the literature on board composition and firm performance
column114: and related soft and hard regulations. It reports that independent and female directors have specific individual characteristics that may influence the overall impact of the regulation (soft or hard). Furthermore
column115: it shows that while independent directors have become key players inside the boardroom through committee assignment
column116: women still face an indirect inner glass ceiling that may jeopardize the efficiency of the quota.'
column156: 'name': 'Le conseil d’administration: enjeux de gouvernance et de responsabilité'
column158: 'description': ""Cet article se propose de faire le point sur les recherches en gouvernance d'entreprises. Les principales thématiques sont illustrées à partir de chiffres sur les conseils d’administration des sociétés du SBF120 pour la période 2007-2015. Dans une première partie
column159: on s’intéresse au fonctionnement du conseil : il s’agit d’une question centrale mais
column160: du fait d’un manque d’informations ou de données disponibles
column161: encore peu couverte par la recherche. La deuxième partie traite de la composition du conseil ; la littérature académique y est beaucoup plus fournie. On identifie un déplacement des préoccupations
column162: de la question de l’indépendance à celle de la diversité. La dernière partie s’attache plus spécifiquement à la diversité de genre au sein des conseils
column163: compte tenu de l’importance qu’a prise cette question depuis quelques années. Au terme de cette revue
column164: il apparaît que le conseil est véritablement l’organe de pouvoir central des grandes sociétés de capitaux
column165: dont l’étude éclaire aussi bien les enjeux de performance
column166: de gouvernance et de responsabilité des entreprises.""

column287: 'name': ""Quota législatif vs. code de gouvernance : quels effets sur la parité Femmes/Hommes dans les conseils d'administration ? Une étude sur données britaniques et françaises""
column288: 'publisher': 'GIP Mission de recherche Droit et Justice'
column289: 'description': 'L’objectif de ce chapitre est d’étudier l’effectivité comparée de la hard law (loi) et de la soft law (code). Notre hypothèse est que des véhicules (supports
column292: produits au terme de processus de production juridique différents et dotés de modes d’application et de mise en oeuvre différents
column295: des effets eux – mêmes différents. Notre question est donc la suivante : la même disposition de gouvernance produit-elle des effets différents
column296: selon qu’elle soit portée par du droit légiféré (hard law) ou un code (soft law) ?\nPrécisément
column297: nous nous intéressons aux effets comparés d’une même disposition juridique
column298: destinée à promouvoir la parité entre femmes et hommes dans les conseils d’administration
column299: selon que cette disposition soit portée par un code de gouvernance d’entreprise ou par une loi (sous la forme d’un quota législatif). En d’autres termes
column300: nous étudions les effets d’un « choc régulatoire » (l’introduction
column302: d’une disposition similaire concernant la parité femmes / hommes par un code et un texte de loi respectivement
column303: en Grande-Bretagne et en France) sur la composition des conseils d’administration des entreprises des deux pays concernés. Notre objectif est de déterminer si les résultats observés aujourd’hui en termes de mixité genrée des conseils d’administration dans les deux pays
column305: peuvent s’expliquer par le choix du code ou de la loi (ou le quota législatif) pour promouvoir l’égalité femmes / hommes dans les conseils d’administration. Nous vérifions évidemment que les différences de performance actuelles des entreprises britanniques et françaises en matière d’égalité femmes / hommes dans les conseils ne sont pas imputables à d’autres facteurs que le choix du code vs. le quota législatif pour atteindre l’équilibre genré des conseils.'
column347: 'name': ""Gouvernance et Performances d'entreprise : quelle équation de durabilité?""
column349: 'description': ""Cette article est un résumé des travaux de thèse sur la gouvernance d'entreprise et la responsabilité sociétale au travers du prisme des conseils d'administration. column455: 'name': 'Independent directors: less informed but better selected than affiliated directors?'
column457: 'description': 'This paper examines the relationships between independence
column458: director unobservable ability and firm performance. We develop an original empirical strategy based on the AKM model to estimate separately director fixed effects (as a measure of individual ability) and firm fixed effects. We show that board independence has an ambiguous impact on corporate performance because of two opposing forces: one related to the director nomination process
column459: the other one related to board functioning. On one hand
column460: we report that independence is positively correlated with individual fixed effects
column461: an evidence consistent with a nomination process of independent directors based on individual ability. On the other hand
column465: is negatively correlated with firm performance suggesting that independent board members experience an informational deficit (as compared to affiliated directors).'
column507: 'name': 'Board independence and operating performance: analysis on (French) company and individual data'
column509: 'description': 'This article studies the relationship between board independence and firm operating performance in French listed companies. We take advantage of an original database
column510: with a time-series dimension that can be used to mitigate heterogeneity and dynamic endogeneity issues. In addition
column511: this database can be disaggregated at the individual (director) level. This design enables us to introduce firm fixed effects and individual fixed effects in firm performance equations
column512: thereby controlling for heterogeneity at the firm and individual levels. Our main result is to document a significant negative relationship between independence and accounting performance. This result suggests that
column514: the costs of independence (i.e. the informational gap supported by independent directors compared to insiders and affiliated directors) outweigh the benefits of independence (i.e. the reduction in agency costs).'

column17: 'name': '""La Phénoménologie de Maurice Merleau-Ponty peut-elle servir de source d\'inspiration à l\'esthéticien industriel ?""\u200b'
column20: 'description': '""Can Maurice Merleau-Ponty\'s Phenomenology serve as an inspiration for the industrial designer ?""\u200b\n\nWhile methodically studying ""Phenomenology of Perception""\u200b by French mid 20th century philosopher Maurice Merleau-Ponty
column21: I did my utmost to prove that
column22: not only his philosophy and industrial design were born around the same time
column23: but they were also based on the same considerations. \nHis vision of human life is constructed on the concepts of perception
column24: surrounding natural world and perceiving body
column25: forming human behavior. This human condition is therefor undetermined but one can transcend this condition by making sense in what surrounds one. His conception of the object is what makes this philosophy interesting for the industrial designer. Merleau-Ponty considers that we perceive each ""human object""\u200b function
column26: as we ""experiment""\u200b the object with our body ; moreover each ""human object""\u200b is above all a ""natural object""\u200b
column27: so it can - and must - tend toward nature\'s harmony where everything expresses its inherent meaning. I link those concepts to the first industrial designers\'\u200b theories : Raymond Loewy in ""Never leave well enough alone""\u200b (1951) and Henry Dreyfuss in ""Designing for people""\u200b (1955). I also question the origin of this historical renewed appreciation of the human body.\nThis philosophical approach to industrial design is finally supposed to put some sense back to our material life
column29: within today\'s context of economic crisis
column31: and constant reflection on moral or identity. When industrial design makes our everyday life better
column32: makes us meet our fellow man through the object
column34: doesn\'t it tie in with philosophy on one of its main reason : the pursuit of happiness?'

column17: 'description': 'The Political Economy of Government Auditing addresses the elusive quest for greater transparency and accountability in the management of public finances in emerging economies; and
column19: it examines the contribution of autonomous audit agencies to the fight against corruption and waste.\n\n""This book is an important contribution to our understanding of how corruption can be prevented by strengthening those institutions tasked with scrutinizing government and overseeing public finances. It provides useful lessons to reformers in Latin America in their efforts to promote integrity in the use of public resources. These lessons of experience are also relevant for African countries pursuing the same objectives. "" Donald Kaberuka
column20: President of the African Development Bank and former Minister of Finance of Rwanda\n\n""Controlling corruption represents a fundamental challenge for all societies in their quest to improve the lives of the most vulnerable. Carlos Santiso eloquently demonstrates the importance of strengthening the institutions of integrity to combat corruption and
column22: enhance transparency and accountability in public finances. His analysis of the role of audit agencies will undoubtedly help reformers around the world in the fight against corruption and hopefully inspire others to further enhance our knowledge of these overlooked oversight institutions."" - Dr. Peter Eigen
column23: Founder of Transparency International\n\n""The book stresses in various places that
column25: the effectiveness of audit agencies does not depend only on organizational factors but also
column27: on the influence of political factors. For this reason these institutions cannot be copied from other countries and cannot be created over night. They must be created over a period of time and reflect the political reality of the countries. Dr. Santiso’s book is of particularly great value in this context."" - Vito Tanzi

column74: 'description': 'Behavioral sciences help refine our understanding of human decision-making. Their insights are immensely relevant for policy-making
column75: since public intervention works much better when it targets real people rather than imaginary beings assumed to be perfectly rational. Increasingly
column76: governments around the world are keen to rely on those insights for reshaping public interventions in a wide range of policy areas
column80: and data protection. When policy-making meets behavioral sciences
column81: effective and low-cost regulations can emerge in the form of default rules
column83: and simplification requirements. While behaviorally-informed intervention has a huge potential for policymaking
column84: it also attracts legitimacy and practicability concerns. This book takes a European perspective on those issues and explores the legal implications of the emergent phenomenon of behavioral regulation by focusing on the challenges and opportunities it may offer to EU policy-making and beyond. It will be a fascinating read for academics and practitioners working in the field of European law and consumer law
column85: as well as for policymakers. (Series: Modern Studies in European Law) [Subject: EU Law

column164: 'name': 'Nudging legally: On the Checks and Balances of Behavioural Regulation'
column166: 'description': 'As behavioral sciences are unearthing the complex cognitive framework in which people make decisions
column167: policymakers seem increasingly ready to design behaviorally informed regulations to induce behavior change in the interests of the individual and society. After discussing what behavioral sciences have to offer to administrative law
column168: this article explores the extent to which administrative law may accommodate their findings into the regulatory process. After presenting the main regulatory tools capable of operationalizing behavioral insights
column169: it builds a case for integrating them into public policymaking. In particular
column170: it identifies the need to develop a legal framework capable of ensuring that behavioral considerations may inform the regulatory process while at the same time guaranteeing citizens’ constitutional rights and freedoms vis-à-vis the regulatory state.'

column60: 'description': 'There is little political acknowledgment with regards to the impelling role nationally significant squares can have in revolutions. Inspired by David Siddhartha Patel’s original “Tahrir square model”
column61: our study aims to expand upon his work and test
column62: on a more global scale than his original Middle Eastern scope
column63: the role that geopolitically-important squares can play in spurring revolutionary fervor and subsequently
column64: instigating a revolution. Whilst in our study we found that important squares proved to have no significant effect in influencing revolutions
column65: there are a number of unaccounted for confounders which we were unable to include within our project. Due to this
column66: we believe that a more extensive research on the link between the two variables could eventually suggest a complex relationship.'
column67: 'title': '‘What effect does the presence of a nationally significant square have in influencing a revolution?’'}
